  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear to come from legitimate sources. This is typically done by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers, investments, or commercial transactions to obscure its origin.\n\nThe illegality of money laundering is due to its association with criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism financing, fraud, corruption, and other forms of organized crime. By making illicit funds appear legitimate, money laundering undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates criminal enterprises, and can have broader economic and social impacts.\n\nMost countries have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions and other businesses to monitor and report suspicious transactions. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and significant prison sentences for individuals or entities involved. International cooperation through organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) also plays a key role in combating money laundering globally.",
